         b'\t\n\t\t<!--  Plugin inserted: [begin] -->\n\t\t\t\r\n<div class="'
         b'news-single-item">\r\n\t\t<h2>Computer-Aided Verification award for '
         b'Peter O\'Hearn</h2>\r\n\t\t<div class="newsImage"><a href="index.'
         b'php?eID=tx_cms_showpic&amp;file=5905&amp;md5=8ffbda55986394d6c3fd275'
         b'0f40aa929d75df4d2&amp;parameters%5B0%5D=YTo0OntzOjU6IndpZHRoIjtzOjQ6'
         b'IjgwMG0iO3M6NjoiaGVpZ2h0IjtzOjM6IjYw&amp;parameters%5B1%5D=MCI7czo3O'
         b'iJib2R5VGFnIjtzOjQyOiI8Ym9keSBiZ0NvbG9yPSIjZmZmZmZmIiBz&amp;paramete'
         b'rs%5B2%5D=dHlsZT0ibWFyZ2luOjA7Ij4iO3M6NDoid3JhcCI7czozNzoiPGEgaHJlZj'
         b'0iamF2&amp;parameters%5B3%5D=YXNjcmlwdDpjbG9zZSgpOyI%2BIHwgPC9hPiI7f'
         b'Q%3D%3D" onclick="openPic(\'http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/index.php?eID'
         b'=tx_cms_showpic&amp;file=5905&amp;md5=8ffbda55986394d6c3fd2750f40aa9'
         b'29d75df4d2&amp;parameters%5B0%5D=YTo0OntzOjU6IndpZHRoIjtzOjQ6IjgwMG0'
         b'iO3M6NjoiaGVpZ2h0IjtzOjM6IjYw&amp;parameters%5B1%5D=MCI7czo3OiJib2R5'
         b'VGFnIjtzOjQyOiI8Ym9keSBiZ0NvbG9yPSIjZmZmZmZmIiBz&amp;parameters%5B2%'
         b'5D=dHlsZT0ibWFyZ2luOjA7Ij4iO3M6NDoid3JhcCI7czozNzoiPGEgaHJlZj0iamF2&'
         b'amp;parameters%5B3%5D=YXNjcmlwdDpjbG9zZSgpOyI%2BIHwgPC9hPiI7fQ%3D%3D'
         b"','0a871f49a930d8ac79b812b66e2a12b7','width=800,height=520,status=0,"
         b'menubar=0\'); return false;" target="thePicture"><img src="typo3t'
         b'emp/_processed_/csm_Peter_O_Hearn_8c3dfcc850.jpg" width="200" height'
         b'="130"   alt=""  border="0" /></a><p class="news-single-imgcaption" '
         b'style="width:200px;"></p></div>\r\n\t\t<p>Professor <a href="http://'
         b'www0.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/P.OHearn/" title="Opens external link in new'
         b' window" target="_top" class="external-link-new-window">Peter O\''
         b'Hearn</a> was one of seven researchers to share the 2016 CAV (Comput'
         b'er-Aided Verification) Award. \r</p>\n<p>The annual CAV Award was '
         b'established in 2008 by the steering committee of the CAV conference,'
         b' which is the premier international event for reporting research on '
         b'computer-aided verification, a sub-discipline of Computer Science th'
         b'at is concerned with ensuring that software and hardware systems ope'
         b'rate correctly and reliably.\r</p>\n<p> The 2016 CAV Award was giv'
         b'en on July 21, 2016, at the <a href="http://i-cav.org/2016/" title="'
         b'Opens external link in new window" target="_top" class="external-lin'
         b'k-new-window">28th annual CAV conference held in Toronto</a>, to Jos'
         b'h Berdine, Cristiano Calcagno, Dino Distefano, Samin Ishtiaq, <a hre'
         b'f="http://www0.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/P.OHearn/" title="Opens external l'
         b'ink in new window" target="_top" class="external-link-new-window">Pe'
         b"ter O'Hearn</a>, John Reynolds, and Hongseok Yang for their pioneeri"
         b'ng work on \xe2\x80\x9cSeparation Logic\xe2\x80\x9d. The award cit'
         b'ation acknowledges these researchers&nbsp;\r</p>\n<p>&quot;<i>For '
         b'the development of Separation Logic and for demonstrating its applic'
         b'ability in the automated verification of programs that mutate data s'
         b'tructures</i>&quot;.\r</p>\n<p>Professor O\xe2\x80\x99Hearn is a me'
         b'mber of the <a href="http://pplv.cs.ucl.ac.uk/" title="Opens externa'
         b'l link in new window" target="_top" class="external-link-new-window"'
         b'>Programming Principles, Logic, and Verification research group</a> '
         b'in UCL CS, and also an Engineering manager at Facebook. He cofounded'
         b' a verification startup, Monoidics, in 2013, which developed a verif'
         b'ication tool based on Separation Logic; Monoidics was acquired by Fa'
         b"cebook in 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;\r</p>\n<p>UCL's PPLV group plays a lea"
         b'ding role in the research area recognised by the CAV award. &nbsp;Th'
         b'e head of group, <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/cs_people/D.Pym.ht'
         b'ml/" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_top" class="'
         b'external-link-new-window">Prof David Pym</a>, collaborated with '
         b'O\xe2\x80\x99Hearn on some of the foundational work that led to S'
         b'eparation Logic. <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/cs_people/J.Brothe'
         b'rston.html" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_top" '
         b'class="external-link-new-window">Dr James Brotherston</a> and <a hre'
         b'f="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/cs_people/I.Sergey.html" title="Opens ext'
         b'ernal link in new window" target="_top" class="external-link-new-win'
         b'dow">Dr Ilya Sergey</a> have also made significant contributions on '
         b'the automation of Separation Logic and on its application to reasoni'
         b'ng about concurrent programs. Peter also recently received the <a hr'
         b'ef="https://www.acm.org/media-center/2016/may/goedel-prize-2016" tit'
         b'le="Opens external link in new window" target="_top" class="external'
         b'-link-new-window">2016 Godel prize</a> for the invention of Concurre'
         b'nt Separation Logic. \r</p>\n<p>Head of the UCL-CS <a href="http:/'
         b'/pplv.cs.ucl.ac.uk/" title="Opens external link in new window" targe'
         b't="_top" class="external-link-new-window">Programming Principles, Lo'
         b'gic, and Verification</a> group commented:\r</p>\n<p>&quot;<i>Sepa'
         b'ration Logic is a beautiful mathematical tool that helps to solve si'
         b'gnificant engineering problems. Teams with the ability to deliver at'
         b' the highest level across that theory-to-application spectrum are ve'
         b'ry rare indeed; Josh, Dino, Samin, Hongseok, John, and Peter form on'
         b'e of the very best around.&nbsp; When we began work on the underlyin'
         b'g logical and semantic theory almost 20 years ago, the impact on pro'
         b'gram analysis and verification that Separation Logic would have was '
         b'not merely unknown, but quite unknowable. Moreover, the engineering '
         b'challenges in developing the industry-strength&nbsp; tools that are '
         b'now in place have been formidable. Peter and the team have done an o'
         b'utstanding job.</i>&quot;\r</p>\n<h3> The Award-Winning Contributi'
         b'on</h3>\n<p> Separation Logic is an extension of Hoare logic that'
         b' allows reasoning about heap structures and pointer manipulation. Th'
         b'e heap is the key aspect of imperative programs that makes their ver'
         b'ification difficult, as compared to hardware designs or functional p'
         b'rograms, especially, compositional reasoning about heap manipulating'
         b' programs is particularly hard. Separation Logic provides the fundam'
         b'ental paradigm for achieving that, especially by introducing the cru'
         b'cial concept of the \xe2\x80\x9cseparating conjunction\xe2\x80\x9d'
         b'. This was a real breakthrough that changed our way of thinking, and'
         b' opened the door to a wide field of research that lead to the develo'
         b'pment of efficient verification tools for heap manipulating programs'
         b'.\r</p>\n<p> Separation Logic has been developed in a series of pa'
         b'pers published between the years of 2000 to 2002, co-authored by Pet'
         b'er O\xe2\x80\x99Hearn, John Reynolds, Samin Ishtiaq, and Hongseok'
         b' Yang. This fundamental work was building on early work by Burstall '
         b'in early 70\xe2\x80\x99s and by O\xe2\x80\x99Hearn and Pym in late'
         b' 90\xe2\x80\x99s on Bunched Logic.&nbsp;\r</p>\n<p> Then, after the'
         b' discovery of the logic, a team formed by Josh Berdine, Cristiano Ca'
         b'lcagno, Dino Distefano, Peter O\xe2\x80\x99Hearn and Hongseok Yan'
         b'g, undertook the challenge of demonstrating the use of Separation Lo'
         b'gic in practice. This group of researchers developed a series of pro'
         b'totype tools for automated program verification exploiting Separatio'
         b'n Logic (tools such as Space Invader and Smallfoot), and applied the'
         b'se tools successfully to significant industrial-size case studies. T'
         b'he design of these tools was based on new decision procedures for us'
         b'eful fragments of the logic as well as on efficient techniques for a'
         b'bstract program analysis (using abstract interpretation and) partly '
         b'building on the principles of the \xe2\x80\x9cShape Analysis\xe2'
         b'\x80\x9d defined by Sagiv, Reps and Wilhelm, and introducing the k'
         b'ey concept of bi-abduction. The work of this team was absolutely cru'
         b'cial in making separation logic very popular in our research communi'
         b'ty.\r</p>\n<p>More generally, the work of the winners of 2016 CAV '
         b'award had an important and deep impact on our community and is certa'
         b'inly among the major contributions to the area of formal methods and'
         b' automated verification in the last two decades. The research around'
         b' Separation Logic is still very active. Following the work initiated'
         b' by the group of awardees, many researchers are nowadays working on '
         b'both fundamental and practical issues related to Separation Logic an'
         b'd its use in efficient verification tools. Other examples of the imp'
         b'act of Separation Logic are the SLAyer tool developed at Microsoft, '
         b'which was applied there to device drivers, and the Infer tool develo'
         b'ped and currently used at Facebook for the verification of mobile ap'
         b'plications.\r</p>\n\n\r\n\t\t<div class="clearblock"></div>\r\n\t\t'
